segments.text: and I probably made a mistake and recorded on top of the A side of tape number one, part of what Fred has been sharing.
We're now, and he is sharing with us his experiences with the Student Judicial Board.
FRED PODESTA.
Or the Judicial Board, the J Board, as it was called.
DAVID BURRAGE.
The J Board.
that they charged him with failure to- No, I was taken before the J Board, which by the way was all appointed by me.
I was taken before the J Board for failure to implement legislation which had been enacted by the previous student senate.
And that was a requirement that the students be given an opportunity to vote confidence or no confidence in all the professors.
And that this information be made available.
to students such that when they registered for the spring semester that they would have this knowledge at hand.
A piece of legislation, by the way, which I opposed as a student senator, but didn't have to vote because I was speaker.
In any event, the guy who was responsible for putting this legislation together, who'd been the vice president for academic affairs,
got angry with me because I didn't do it.
And so he filed charges against me before the Judicial Board, which, as I said, I appointed all the members.
And ironically, I got off on a technicality.
And the technicality was that ultimately the charges were moved because since it had to be done in December and he didn't take me to the J Board until February,
It was too late, so it couldn't be enforced anyway.
But it was kind of fun there for two or three weeks, being the center of attention in terms of legislation that I refused to implement as student body president.
Some of the other things that we were engaged in during that time frame, I had a couple of unpopular things that I was involved in.
We had a fairly unsuccessful program where student government had been trying to help decrease
the cost of textbooks for students.
And we ran a thing called, it was actually a co-op kind of a deal, but we ran a thing called Bookmark.
And we ran into one of the traditional problems associated with student-run volunteer organizations.
couldn't pay anything to anybody, and so it was kind of hard to run the thing.
And so we finally reached the conclusion that it was something that needed to be shut down.
So I got the chance to shut down Bookmark.

We also rented refrigerators, which is an interesting concept because the refrigerators, and again, another thing that required manpower, refrigerators were rented by kids who lived in the dorm, which got to the whole question of whether or not kids could have alcohol in dorms and what rules we
were able to deal with in terms of what the use of alcohol on university property.
And fortunately, we worked very well with the folks over at the university officials on the rules and regulations committee to come up with a program of work in that regard.
We also, back early during that time frame, and this is really neat since we're about to have a dedication of this soon on campus, and I had the opportunity
20 years later to both piece of legislation to create a daycare center.
The nature of the student population was changing.

And back during the time that I was student body president, we pursued rather strongly the idea of trying to create a daycare facility on campus for married kids who both parents were going to school, but they didn't have any daycare facilities.
And I'm quite proud that we're at that point now, 20 years later, at the university.
We toured around with creating a food co-op, another opportunity to try to save kids money.
But we kept running into this, how do you fund it kind of a scenario.
But I think they were great ideas.
During that time frame, too, we got very involved in external affairs in terms of involvement in the governance of the city of College Station.
which we thought was important.
Because since we had such a large number of students living there, and many of them were living off campus, that their lives were affected by decisions that were made by the city council.
So we had regular representation there in terms of their meetings.
And we very often got in the mix to some of the stuff that they were discussing.
Two, we had a lot of involvement in Austin.
in terms of what the Texas legislature was doing during that period of time.
One of the big fights that we always had, which is of course one that continues probably even to this day, is how we divided up student service fees.
It was the annual ritual that we went through, not unlike the federal budget process.
And going through the process of how much money the athletic department got and how much went to the various other activities associated with running student-related activities on campus.
And it's now about 10 or 11 till.
I don't know whether they're here yet, so we can't be.
Let's see.
Do you remember any, let's talk about people that you wish you could thank.
Faculty members that really you remember with pride, joy, gratitude?
The one with anger, I can't remember his name.
Actually, you know, I,
I really, really had...
I mean, I could probably go down the list of... Who would you want to thank most?
Who were at the top of the list?
Your gratitude.
I guess probably thanking most would be...
This is dangerous because a lot of these people are still alive.
But I guess probably...
I cannot not
It is very difficult for me to pick out one, and the reason to pick that is difficult is because various ones among them, we had an interface that was different.
For example, if you take out the student services piece, the student activities leadership piece, you know, John Colas,
Stan's head and shoulders because he was the one that I spent most of my time with because of his capacity.
But then within that mix, you got Carol Nadair, who really was the one who sort of held with student government in particular.
And frankly, I served as student body president during that period of time when Dr. Williams was ill.
And Clyde Freeman was acting president of Texas A&M University during the time that I was student vice president.
And I used to kid him and say that we got away with murder because all he was concerned about was finance anyway.
So therefore, we could get away with whatever we wanted, even though I had great times with Jack Williams prior to that.
But I guess on the student services side, it's probably him.
And you put into that mix, too, Bob Boone,
That gave me not only a cultural experience, but a fun experience to do something I liked a whole lot.
I would have great guy who I think took and did just virtually the impossible task in terms of making that work for the city cadets and thus for the university.
What about over the people that- On the academic side- That taught you and- Yeah, on the academic side, I probably would have to stick most with those folks in my college.
and more specifically within my department, you know, I can't take Dr.
I can't take R.C.
Potts out of the equation because of what he did.
And then I've mentioned both of these other three or four guys earlier, Don Levi and J.C. Gray and Herman Brown because of how they molded and directed me during
on the academic side of the equation.

But you know, those guys, too, were the same kinds of guys that if I had some sort of, whether it was a personal problem or whether it was a personal challenge or whether it was something I wanted to do student government-wise, I wanted to bounce it off of somebody, or whether it was some other sort of challenge, I could see any of those guys any time.
And it was something that I'm most grateful for to this day, the guidance that they provided me.
One of the great things about all of those people I mentioned, and many others too, the thing that I think makes Texas A&M unique in terms of its student leadership opportunities is that

The folks who, the adults, if you will, who are responsible for providing direction were always open to allowing students to make their own choices, allowing students to fail, even if they fail, and allow them to try something new.
In other words, they allowed kids to lead.
Yeah, there were some opportunities.
There were some instances when we wanted to do something that perhaps the administration did not want us to do.
But those were not that many.
I remember one in particular, which is kind of a fun story.
The university had made a decision that it wanted to shut down, I want to say it was Milner Hall, but it was one of the dorms over by the
By Sabisa, there was one of these on air condition, had hanging pipes, showers in the middle of each floor, and restrooms and showers in the middle of each floor.
And it wanted to turn it into, I believe, a math, I think it was a math office building.
It might have been Miller.
It was one of those two over at that Hotard-Miller area.
And we caught wind of it.

And, you know, we thought we came up with these really ingenious arguments that, in fact, one of our guys, one of the guys who was vice president on our team, either had some buddies in there or had lived in there at some point in time.
And we didn't like the thought of taking the dormitory, you know, just shortage of housing.
We could always make that argument.
You want to keep kids on campus and all these kinds of things.
Plus, the kids want to live there.
And these old man professors didn't need any more space.
They had space anyway.
So why are we going to do this?
And we individually lobbied the members of the Board of Regents.
And we rolled the administration.
And the board voted in our favor.
We held it off for a year.

We finally lost, but it was one of those where, and I'll never forget the anger which was expressed to us by the administration for our having the gall to go around their back and go lobby members of the Board of Regents.
Was Freeman or Williams president?
Uh, it was an honor to be president, so, uh, Clyde Wilson.
Clyde, okay.
Clyde Wilson.

Uh, and, uh, because this is something I think had come up through academic affairs, through, I guess, John Calhoun was an academic affairs guy, but the guy who led that was Scott Gregson of Garrison, Texas, who was vice president of finance.
And old Scott said, we've got to lobby the members of the board, and we lobbied everybody.
We've got enough votes on the board of regents to turn, to get them to turn down the request of administration.
It was kind of cool.
Well, let's see, we're...
I don't encourage that now, by the way.
Okay.
